text: You can strangle a bulldog with your bare hands, can't you, anon?

Third, the Church is not the daughter of Christ - the Church is the BRIDE of Christ. By calling her His daughter, we are led to believe that she is "left after" Christ, while, in reality, He has never left her, but remains, and actively participates in all of her sacraments.

Second, Christ is called "king of the Mages" - notice how Levy capitalizes the latter, while not the title, referring to Him. Magic is a very unchristian thing and calling Christ the king of magicians is, in my opinion, a form of mockery - like calling satan "the king of saints".

First, even though the Resurrection changed the world on a metaphysical level, magic as a phenomenon is only weakened, and does not cease to exist. By trying to portray it as no longer effective, the author seeks to soothe and sedate all occult-interested readers.

By comparing occultists to priests, Levy is making a mockery of church and priesthood - the same as saying that a demon is a "dissident angel".

Practicing magic is absolutely not "competing" with priests, but a highly forbidden and dangerous dark art.

Priests are NOT magicians.

Fifth, saying that practicing magic is "being a dissident priest" is completely wrong and slanderous, as no priest uses any form of magic.

This you really gotta remember and understand - ALL magic is bad and ruinous, there is NO magic in the church. What priests do is NOT magic.

Fourth, religious garments, sacraments etc. like a cross you carry on your neck, prayer ropes, catholic scapulars, medals etc. are NOT a talisman and do not work as a form of magic.

In the church, there exist zero forms of magic, and prayer is not magic. There is NO good magic.

Finally, and worst of all: saying that priests evoke God in a similar fashion as necromancers commune with the dead. I would really, really, REALLY suggest watching this very short (THREE MINUTE) video on the topic. Boyan explains best. LISTEN: youtube.com/watch?v=vuvoATZB‚Ä¶

Comparing talismans to rosaries or witch gatherings to Christian monasticism is highly wrong and an outright lie. If anything, the Christian sacraments are the INVERSE of the things Levy mentions in the text.

At the end of the short text, the blasphemy is truly visible - it is the mockery of comparing different Christian traditions and sacraments to Pagan or outright occultist and satanic "equivalents".

The mysteries of the church do NOT have ANY equivalent outside of the church.
